<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-329-639  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 329 639.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Datamation  Feb 1 1989 v35 n3 p77(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Cahners Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Slowdown begins in the IS industry. (information systems)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Franchi, Madeline.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>The purchase of information systems will slow down in 1989, butgrowth will continue.andP;  The purchase of computer and officeequipment grew to $50.92 billion in the first nine months of 1988,up 11 percent over the same period in 1987.andP;  Communicationsequipment accounted for $29.62 billion, up 7.4 percent over theyear-earlier period.andP;  The growth began to slow down at the end of1988, and the slide is expected to continue through 1989.andP;  USCommerce Department figures project only a one-percent gain insales for office and computer equipment.andP;  Communications equipmentsales are expected to decline by one percent.andP;  However, theforecasts point out that the dip will be short-lived, as strongergrowth is expected in 1990.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Information SystemsMarket AnalysisGrowthExpendituresForecastingPurchasesStatistics.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   Slowing IT shipments. (graph)Growing IT share of purchases. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Slowdown Begins in the IS industry.andM;In the waning months of 1988, evidence began filtering in that the latestbusiness cycle expansion for the information processing industry was comingto a close.andP;  This is not to say that sales won't increase at all in 1989, butthe rate of growth will be diminutive compared with the 1988 recovery.andP;  Aweaker U.S.andP;  economy, a pull-back in business investments, and a reduction inexport gains translate into dwindling growth in the computer andcommunications equipment markets.andM;Through the first three quarters of 1988, U.S.andP;  factory shipments of computerand office equipment amounted to $50.92 billion, a hike of roughly 11% overthe first nine months of 1987.andP;  Shipments of commercial communicationsequipment did not advance quite as strongly, but still jumped to $29.62billion--7.4% over the comparable time period in 1987.andP;  Once all of the datefor 1988 is tabulated, the annual increases will be close to these percentageamounts.andM;In 1989, however, the increase in computer and office equipment shipments isexpected to measure just over 1%, while sales of communications equipmentwill actually decline by 1%.andP;  Compared with the losses that occurred back in1986, though, this contraction will be both mild and short-lived.andP;  Shipmentsof information processing equipment will turn around again in mid- to late1990.andM;Business investment in equipment swelled 13% last year, boosting IS sales,but in 1989, businesses will contribute only an additional 1.8% towardequipment purchases.andP;  However, one factor working to mitigate the downturnfor the information systems industry is the penetration of equipment into theworkplace.andP;  From a 12% share back in 1972, the portion of total equipmentinvestment devoted to the purchase of information processing equipmentskyrocketed to about 45% in 1988.andO;</TEXT></DOC>